Here's the registration:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service: one shared HttpClient and cache for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels: fresh state each time a page is navigated to
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages: transient so each navigation gets a clean page + VM pair
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` / shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps caches consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should start with fresh VM state. A singleton VM would leak stale data between visits. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Paired 1-to-1 with their ViewModel. A new page instance avoids leftover UI state from a previous navigation. |

**When you'd pick Scoped instead:** If you used Shell-based navigation with a "session" concept (e.g., a multi-step wizard), you could register VMs as `AddScoped` so all pages within that scope share the same VM instance — but MAUI doesn't define scopes by default, so transient is the standard choice.
